ked with intriguing discoveries ranging from the surprising anxieties of the rich to the critical role of women in keeping struggling families afloat.  Through tales of stalwart stoicism, heart-wrenching worry, marital angst, and religious conviction, Cut Adrift deepens our understanding of how families are coping in a go-it-alone age—and how the different strategies on which affluent, middle-class, and poor families rely upon not only reflect inequality, but fuel it.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEqualityzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aage of insecurity.  aamerican culture.  aamerican society.  aamerican studies.  aanthropology.  aanxiety.  acase studies.  aclass anxiety.  aclass insecurity.  acultural studies.  adebt.  aeconomic insecurity.  afamily.  afinancial security.  agot it alone age.  ainequality.  amarriage and family.  amarriage.  amiddle class families.  anational conversation.  apoor families.  apoverty.  areligion.  arich.  arisk.  asafety nets.  asecurity.  asocial class.  asocial cost.  asociology.  astandard of living.  astruggling families.  awealth.  awealthy families.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027765640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095845640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958456/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY